07434nam a22009615i 9789815011852DE-B159720230328044521.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230328t20222022si     fo  d z      eng d  a97898150118527 a10.1355/97898150118522doi  a(DE-B1597)651079  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  asicSG 7aSOC0000002bisacsh00aIn Sickness and In Health :bIn Sickness and In Health /ced. by Firman Witoelar, Ariane Utomo. 1aSingapore : bISEAS Publishing, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (276 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tTables -- tFigures -- tContributors -- tAcknowledgements -- tGlossary -- t1 Introduction: Diagnosing Indonesia -- tPART 1 The Indonesian health system: Challenges and opportunities -- t2 Post-pandemic trajectory of healthreform financing in Indonesia -- t3 The right to health and the politics of health policy reform in post–New Order Indonesia -- t4 The importance of the 2020 Population Census for health data -- t5 Addressing regional disparities in access to medical specialists in Indonesia -- t6 Pill pushers: Politics, money and the quality of medicine in Indonesia -- tPART 2 Health for all: Lessons and strategies -- t7 Navigating access to health care in Indonesia: A sociostructural analysis -- t8 Impact of COVID-19 on maternal, neonatal and child health programs: A case study for health systems strengthening -- t9 Maternal health: Past, present and moving forward -- t10 Disability in Indonesia: What can we learn from the available data? -- t11 Out of the shadows: A brief introduction to mental health in Indonesia -- t12 Dengue control in Yogyakarta, Indonesia: Lessons learned from public health innovation using Wolbachia-infected Aedes aegypti mosquitoes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDespite significant improvements in many health outcomes over the past 60 years, many chronic problems in Indonesia’s health system including financial sustainability, governance and inequities in accessing health care have long been apparent, even before the COVID-19 pandemic. The epidemiological transition associated with demographic and socioeconomic change in recent decades makes Indonesia one of many countries that still struggle to address the issues of communicable, maternal and nutritional diseases while facing an increasing burden of non-communicable diseases. The contributors to In Sickness and In Health: Diagnosing Indonesia investigate challenges and opportunities facing the Indonesian health system and assess hurdles that Indonesians have to navigate in their quest to achieve a longer and better quality of life. Politics shaping recent health policy reforms in Indonesia, barriers to the supply of specialist doctors and quality medicines, availability of accurate health and population data, and the financial toll of the COVID-19 pandemic are among the topics discussed in this book. Accessing essential health services for mothers and children and for those living with disability, discrimination and mental illness, as well as an innovative trial to control dengue, are also examined.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aPublic healthzIndonesia. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aCameron, Lisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDewi, Aksari, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDjani, Luky, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFanda, Relmbuss Biljers, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHariadini, Ayuk Lawuningtyas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHasnida, Amalia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rel